WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.836 --> 00:00:07.048
Sometimes I like just to stand
on the top of the first dune,

00:00:07.132 --> 00:00:10.343
looking at
people’s reaction.

00:00:11.511 --> 00:00:12.929
People arrive
and...

00:00:14.431 --> 00:00:16.307
Wow.

00:00:19.728 --> 00:00:21.646
The first time that
I came here,

00:00:21.855 --> 00:00:24.274
I was around
12 years old.

00:00:25.483 --> 00:00:27.152
It was shocking.

00:00:28.028 --> 00:00:31.906
It was a feeling like
to be in another planet.

00:00:32.282 --> 00:00:37.871
 It looks like a desert,
but Lençóis Maranhenses gets more rain

00:00:37.871 --> 00:00:45.503
than Scotland or London, which is
around 1600 millimeters [63 inches] a year.

00:00:45.795 --> 00:00:49.049
So it’s not a desert—
it’s something else.

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:54.387
Lençóis Maranhenses,
on the northeast coast of Brazil,

00:00:54.387 --> 00:01:00.602
sits at the intersection of three biomes—
a rare overlap that supercharges biodiversity.

00:01:00.977 --> 00:01:05.899
Here, a field of dunes spreads across
350 square miles,

00:01:05.899 --> 00:01:10.653
and every year these mountains of sand
migrate up to 80 feet.

00:01:11.529 --> 00:01:17.744
Then during the rainy season, 
thousands of lagoons appear, many big enough to swim in.

00:01:18.286 --> 00:01:21.164
So what makes this surreal
environment possible?

00:01:21.331 --> 00:01:27.170
And why, even after 2 million years in existence,
does it still feel so mysterious?

00:01:34.135 --> 00:01:38.848
Lençóis Maranhenses is the biggest
field of dunes in South America.

00:01:40.475 --> 00:01:43.978
Between these dunes,
during the rainy season

00:01:43.978 --> 00:01:48.525
the water level rises
and they form lagoons.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:55.865
You can never see Lençóis Maranhenses twice
because everything is changing all the time.

00:01:56.032 --> 00:01:59.536
Strong movements
of sand and water

00:01:59.536 --> 00:02:03.832
changing the shapes and
the compositions of the lagoons.

00:02:05.667 --> 00:02:08.169
I spent
almost like a year 

00:02:08.169 --> 00:02:11.131
camping and living
in tents around the park

00:02:11.422 --> 00:02:14.092
and surveying amphibians
and reptiles.

00:02:14.759 --> 00:02:18.429
This opportunity changed
my view of life

00:02:18.513 --> 00:02:22.976
and helped to forge
the biologist that I am today.

00:02:23.852 --> 00:02:27.063
Some visitors arrive there
and wonder why 

00:02:27.063 --> 00:02:29.315
the water
just doesn’t sink.

00:02:31.693 --> 00:02:37.615
Underneath the field of dunes,
there is a rock which traps water

00:02:37.615 --> 00:02:41.077
so it doesn't keep
sinking forever.

00:02:42.704 --> 00:02:45.748
So let’s imagine
there is a bathtub.

00:02:46.749 --> 00:02:51.254
When it rains,
the water level starts to rise.

00:02:51.421 --> 00:02:56.509
And then you can see the water
in the holes in between the dunes,

00:02:56.509 --> 00:02:59.387
so you can see
the lagoons formed.

00:02:59.888 --> 00:03:03.183
And then in the dry season,
the water evaporates.

00:03:03.183 --> 00:03:05.185
The water level
starts to go down again 

00:03:05.602 --> 00:03:06.769
until it gets here. 

00:03:06.769 --> 00:03:08.521
The water is still there. 

00:03:08.521 --> 00:03:08.563
The water is still there. 

00:03:08.563 --> 00:03:10.481
People cannot see it,
but it is still there.

00:03:11.441 --> 00:03:16.237
If this year, a lagoon is in a certain place
in the next year, it will move.

00:03:16.362 --> 00:03:20.408
Because where the lagoon is formed,
the dunes will bury that lagoon.

00:03:20.575 --> 00:03:24.162
And next year, a new lagoon
will emerge further ahead.

00:03:25.330 --> 00:03:30.501
Here, an unusually large tide range
creates a wide beach at low tide.

00:03:30.793 --> 00:03:36.633
Strong winds lift the fine sand
and blow it inland to build new dune ridges.

00:03:38.092 --> 00:03:41.721
The winds come mainly
from the same direction.

00:03:41.888 --> 00:03:47.769
The sand gets dry
and then it can be carried by this strong wind.

00:03:47.894 --> 00:03:51.356
They measured
the size of the grains.

00:03:51.606 --> 00:03:54.484
It’s so little.

00:03:54.984 --> 00:03:57.946
The sand is so soft,
it’s so loose 

00:03:57.946 --> 00:04:02.116
that it flows down the hill
like water. 

00:04:02.158 --> 00:04:03.952
It's beautiful.

00:04:04.702 --> 00:04:12.043
The wind is constantly redrawing paths,
so locals follow wind and ridgelines, not maps.

00:04:13.878 --> 00:04:16.381
I was born and raised here, 
in Ponta do Mangue.

00:04:16.381 --> 00:04:21.010
My parents were born here, my
grandparents were born here

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.304
and we’ve been living here
this whole time.

00:04:26.057 --> 00:04:30.103
Sometimes we go out in the morning,
and it’s windy, the dune is flat. 

00:04:30.103 --> 00:04:33.940
When we return later in the day, 
the dune has a different shape.

00:04:34.148 --> 00:04:37.277
You have to be very careful,
sometimes we get lost.

00:04:37.777 --> 00:04:40.905
The wind erases
all the car tracks.

00:04:41.531 --> 00:04:44.575
Out of nowhere, it creates a dune
in the middle of another.

00:04:44.867 --> 00:04:48.246
Last week, we took a wrong turn
and we kept going.

00:04:48.329 --> 00:04:51.833
Later we realized that 
we were in the wrong path.

00:04:52.083 --> 00:04:55.628
Then we came back again,
so we could continue.

00:04:55.962 --> 00:04:58.214
They call it 
the desert that breathes

00:04:58.256 --> 00:05:01.592
because of the dunes,
the movement of the dunes.

00:05:08.683 --> 00:05:13.104
Everything is destroyed
and rebuilt every single year.

00:05:14.063 --> 00:05:15.815
In the region of Lençóis 

00:05:15.815 --> 00:05:18.109
everything is mixed.

00:05:18.526 --> 00:05:22.405
There are some animals
that occur just there.

00:05:22.530 --> 00:05:26.534
And salt marshes,
very far from the ocean, 

00:05:26.743 --> 00:05:30.872
different from almost
all the others that exist in the world

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:37.295
that usually occur very close to the beach
because it needs this salt.

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:40.757
We have a turtle,
which is Pininga.

00:05:40.882 --> 00:05:42.717
It’s a water tiger turtle.

00:05:43.176 --> 00:05:45.303
It's an endemic species.

00:05:45.303 --> 00:05:49.098
And the park plays
an important role for its conservation,

00:05:49.098 --> 00:05:51.517
because it doesn’t exist
anywhere else.

00:05:51.851 --> 00:05:57.357
And this animal is known to rest,
digging underneath the dunes. 

00:05:57.607 --> 00:06:03.404
So it reduces its metabolism,
waiting for the next rainy season.

00:06:03.988 --> 00:06:07.575
The fish have a life cycle
shorter than one year.

00:06:07.575 --> 00:06:11.704
They leave the eggs
that are resistant to this dryness.

00:06:11.704 --> 00:06:15.875
And when the water comes,
everything comes to life again.

00:06:20.671 --> 00:06:24.050
We are going to
a world of extremes.

00:06:25.259 --> 00:06:28.638
Lençóis,
it’s a micro-laboratory;

00:06:28.971 --> 00:06:31.557
as we increase our knowledge,

00:06:31.724 --> 00:06:35.186
we might find ideas
that may be useful

00:06:35.228 --> 00:06:38.064
on the perspective
of a climactic emergency. 

00:06:42.735 --> 00:06:43.528
Since we live near the dunes,
sometimes we have to move.

00:06:43.528 --> 00:06:43.694
Since we live near the dunes,
sometimes we have to move.

00:06:43.694 --> 00:06:44.946
Since we live near the dunes,
sometimes we have to move.

00:06:44.946 --> 00:06:45.571
Since we live near the dunes,
sometimes we have to move.

00:06:45.571 --> 00:06:47.281
Since we live near the dunes,
sometimes we have to move.

00:06:47.323 --> 00:06:50.660
My father used to live among
those dunes over there.

00:06:51.744 --> 00:06:54.080
The dune kept growing.

00:06:54.288 --> 00:06:58.042
 In our case, in about three, four years,
I think we’ll have to move,

00:06:58.084 --> 00:07:01.462
because the dunes are getting closer
and throwing sand.

00:07:02.171 --> 00:07:04.048
When the lagoons dry up

00:07:04.048 --> 00:07:08.302
we take the fish from the ponds and put them
in the ones that have more water

00:07:08.553 --> 00:07:10.221
so they can survive a little longer, otherwise,
they will die of drought.

00:07:10.221 --> 00:07:13.057
so they can survive a little longer, otherwise,
they will die of drought.

00:07:18.896 --> 00:07:24.485
When I close my eyes
and I think about Lençóis Maranhenses,

00:07:24.694 --> 00:07:31.576
the first thing that comes to my mind
is a dragonfly, flying over a lagoon…

00:07:32.452 --> 00:07:35.121
There are white flowers,

00:07:35.288 --> 00:07:39.125
their roots dancing in the water.

00:07:41.419 --> 00:07:47.717
It’s a place that can really
change people’s mind and soul and heart.

00:07:48.092 --> 00:07:52.388
And they say,
“for the first time I’m breathing.”

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:57.268
Very special place. 

00:07:57.268 --> 00:07:57.935
Sorry.

00:08:04.066 --> 00:08:06.194
When I pass away,

00:08:06.194 --> 00:08:12.533
 I’d like them to burn me and put my ashes
moving from lakes to lakes.

00:08:12.950 --> 00:08:15.661
Moving with the wind,
with the water.

00:08:18.039 --> 00:08:21.167
To be part of it,
forever.

